Unit Modifications

Click a tile to show that unit's modifications. Use the search box to filter.

Hammer_Sniper

Overview

This modification of the hammer battle tank is used in stationary combat where it can outrange most other early game units. It pairs best with other units in front of it to soak up damage like for example using Fortresses or Assault Infantry.

Scenarios like driving them into the Chameleon's cloud to reveal hidden enemy units should be avoided due to their slower speed and lower tankyness. For this same reason they are also much more vulerable to counterattacks with aviation like Dragonflies or Hawks.

A less effective, but still viable way to use them is to kite enemy units like Grenadiers or Armadillos. Just remember that it can no longer outrun Armadillo!

Disadvantages
Has reduced Hitpoints
Has reduced Speed
Has increased Production Time
Has reduced Firerate
Has reduced Explosion Radius
Advantages
Has increased Vision Range
Has increased Attack Range
Has increased Accuracy while stationary
Has increased Damage against Armor 2
Has increased Damage against Armor 3

Hammer_Heavy

Overview

This modification of the hammer battle tank is a good choice to dominate the early and mid stages of a battle, as it has far superior direct combat power and tankyness than its normal counterpart. It has noticeably reduced speed though, which makes it much easier for enemy units to escape from it, or for Salamander to kite it.

For this same reason he can no longer easily catch up with an army hidden under the chameleon's fog and is therefore most effective before Headquarters level 4.

While by no means an actual counter, the increased stats and in particular its higher explosion radius make it much more capable of fighting off enemy infantry like Riflemen.

Disadvantages
Has reduced Speed
Has increased Production Cost
Has increased Production Time
Has reduced Fire Rate
Advantages
Has increased Hitpoints
Has increased Armor
Has increased Explosion Radius
Has increased Damage against Armor 1
Has increased Damage against Armor 2
Has increased Damage against Armor 3

Zeus_Quickshot

Overview

This modification of the heavy assault tank Zeus specialises in versatility by converting its secondary weapon into an anti air system. This allows it to counter small aviation attacks without the support of dedicated anti air units like typhoon, but comes at the cost of increased cost and command point requirements.

In general he is always capable of contributing to a fight, no matter which type of army the enemy makes, but might require the help of heroes like Beholder, Psion, Solaris and Atlas to make up for its reduced explosion radius on the main weapon which is a key stat to counter Chameleon.

His anti air system, due to its relatively low damage, works best when combined with other more tanky units like Energy Shields or Heroes. Using him with torrents is not recommended therefore.

Especially at lower ranks, where his body turn speed is still slower, he can struggle much more than normal against Armadillos, because he no longer has any ground targeting missiles, but is still an effective counter to them.

His increased tankyness also makes him much more resistant to area of effect damage like Leviathan's devastation ability or Albatross bombings.

Disadvantages
Has increased Production Cost
Has increased Command Point Cost
Thermoelectric Gun has reduced Accuracy
Thermoelectric Gun has reduced Explosion Radius
Missile Launcher can no longer target infantry
Missile Launcher can no longer target Vehicles
Missile Launcher can no longer target Ships
Advantages
Has increased Hitpoints
Has increased Armor
Missile Launcher has increased Attack Range
Missile Launcher has increased Damage against Armor 1
Missile Launcher has increased Damage against Armor 2
Missile Launcher has increased Damage against Armor 3
Missile Launcher can target Fighters

Torrent_Shotgun

Overview

This modification of the multiple launch rocket system Torrent shifts Torrent slightly from a siege into a more direct combatant unit. He achieves this by sacrificing part of his range which makes him less capable of taking out the enemy bases' defenses. This also makes him more vulnerable to enemy air strikes and mammoth as he needs to be closer to his target.

He also shoots smaller salvos which reduces his chances of killing enemies with a single salvo. But in turn his overall fire rate is noticeably higher, which allows him to target enemies more often which over time actually gives him more firepower than a normal Torrent.

Combined with his much faster siege and unsiege time, and a reduction in the hidden statistics targeting time and missile speed, he is much more capable of hitting enemies that are on the move, therefore making up for one of the biggest weaknesses of the normal torrent.

If enemy units manage to get close enough to attack him, he is much more capable of surviving the encounter as he posesses improved armor in march and especially in stationary mode.

Furthermore his increased movement speed ensures that he no longer moves slower than the remainder of your army.

Disadvantages
Has increased Production Cost
Has reduced Attack Range
Advantages
Has increased Firerate
Has increased Speed
Has increased Firerate

Viking_Marauder

Overview

This modification of the heavy destroyer Viking shifts him into a more offensive ship. For this he sacrifices his ability to withstand damage, which makes him more vulnerable to aviation. In exchange he gains improved firepower against surface targets and additional attack range.

Through this he is much better at positional warfare as he can be placed in such a way that he shoots standard alligators without them shooting back unless they close the distance and therefore abandon their formation. This same ability also allows him to not get kited by Salamander too.

While his overall firepower is higher than before, his capability to deal damage to enemy submarines overall decreases. He still counters them, but you need to invest significantly more vikings if you want to deal with barracudas now.

Against land targets he performs slightly better than a normal Viking as he can shoot further inland, but his lowered hitpoints also mean that units like Jaguars can much more quickly counter kill this Viking modification as well.

Disadvantages
Has decreased Hitpoints
Has increased Production Cost
Thermoelectric Gun has reduced Firerate
Torpedo Launcher has reduced Firerate
Advantages
Thermoelectric Gun has increased Attack Range
Thermoelectric Gun has increased Damage against Armor 1
Thermoelectric Gun has increased Damage against Armor 2
Thermoelectric Gun has increased Damage against Armor 3
Torpedo Launcher has increased Attack Range
Torpedo Launcher has increased Damage against Armor 1
Torpedo Launcher has increased Damage against Armor 2
Torpedo Launcher has increased Damage against Armor 3

Typhoon_Speedwagon

Overview

This modification of the anti-aircraft vehicle Typhoon shifts him from from a stationary siege unit into a mobile anti air that is much more similar to its resistance counterpart. To achieve this he sacrifices his siege mode, but gains notable improvement to his stats that can be used while on the move.

Similar to porcupines this modification is capable of chasing after Leviathan when it tries to escape from the range of typhoons, therefore helping you to finish it off when it is already badly damaged.

Due to no longer needing to siege up this modificaton also works much better with armies that need to stay on the move like for example hammers. In cases like this it is also much more likely to be exposed to enemy unit's attacks, where its increased survivability further help it. He can also be used as support for Solaris if he moved away from the rest of your army as he can much more easily keep up with him.

This comes at the cost of raw combat though, as the lack of a siege mode makes him a much worse choice for any kind of less agile army like with Zeus, Torrent, Psion or Atlas.

Disadvantages
Has increased Production Cost
Has reduced Firerate
Has no Siege Mode
Advantages
Has increased Hitpoints
Has increased Armor
Has increased Vision Range
Has increased Attack Range
Has increased Damage against Armor 1
Has increased Damage against Armor 2
Has increased Damage against Armor 3

Shield_Wide

Overview

This modification of the support combat vehicle Energy Shield makes him a bit harder to use and more expensive to replace once sniped, but in exchange improves his abilities in several ways.

His reduced Hitpoints and slower activation time for his protection field make him noticeably easier to kill with hawks, especially when you get surprised by an air raid targeting your shield vehicles.

At the same time his increased shield radius not only allows him to more easily cover all of your units inside his shield, but also makes it much easier to keep energy shields within each other's protection radius. Furthermore you can keep your Energy Shield a bit further behind your army, which in turn helps protect him from being targeted by enemy units.

He also has increased energy reserves and recovers more energy over the same time period which results in an overall longer usage time for his protection field. Together with the previously mentioned advantage this makes it much more viable to always have 2 shields activated at all times without leaving them unprotected.

Disadvantages
Has reduced Hitpoints
Has increased Production Cost
Has increased Activation Time
Advantages
Has increased Protective Field Radius
Has increased Energy Reserve
Has increased Energy Regeneration
